The Wizard Tradition

The Axiomatic Schools
The Axiomatic Schools emerged after the Spirebound Conclave's catastrophe, founded
on the premise that if magical phenomena are real and consistent, they are subject
to formal analysis, and if subject to formal analysis, the results can be verified
by independent practitioners working from the same premises. The Schools built their
credibility on replication: any practitioner who followed the documented procedures
should achieve the documented results. A procedure that could not be reliably
replicated was either documented incorrectly or was not a genuine phenomenon. This
commitment to replication made Axiomatic documentation exceptionally precise and
exceptionally demanding to produce.

Artificers of Sequence
The Schools' specialized application of formal proof to combat casting produced the
Artificers of Sequence. Their insight was that combat casting was not merely spell
selection but sequence optimization under uncertainty. Given available spells, an
opponent's capabilities, and environmental conditions, what ordering of casts
maximized the probability of a desired outcome at minimum cost? Artificer training
emphasized problem-solving methodology rather than fixed sequences. A practitioner
who had memorized twenty optimal sequences would fail against the twenty-first
context. One who had internalized the methodology could derive the appropriate
sequence for any situation.

Patient Theoreticians
Wizards are described as patient not because they are slow by temperament but
because the Artificer methodology requires accurate assessment before engagement.
A Wizard who engages before assessing the context is not being aggressive; they are
abandoning the methodology that makes them effective. The tactical patience is not
caution but prerequisite. Where Sorcerers command breadth and synthesis, Wizards
command exactitude and sequence. The common name that survived is not a grand title
but a technical one: someone who has made the formless precise.

The Keep and the Legacy
The Wizard's Keep drew substantially on Axiomatic methodology for its governance.
The Triple-Ledger Rule is an application of replication thinking to institutional
oversight: if an operation is legitimate, it can be documented precisely enough for
independent review. Wizard practitioners debate whether the Keep's integration with
registry law represents a compromise of Axiomatic independence or a mature
recognition that accountability to external verification strengthens the formal
methodology rather than weakening it.
